segments.text: Well today is November the 16th and I'm interviewing Dr. Dan Householder who has been at Texas A&M since 1975 and we're going to talk about, has been in the Department of Industrial and Vocational
Education, IBTE.
And we're going to talk a little bit about changes and things that have happened at Texas A&M in the last few years and what kinds of things have affected these changes from your perception.
And you have been department head for the last 10 years.
So a lot of things have happened in this department, I'm sure, as well as in the college and
from your perceptions, what have been some of the major changes?
You could start with your department as you see it, and then maybe go on into the college itself or vice versa.
Well, the college has certainly come along trying to meet contemporary needs.
I think when I came here, there was something of a dichotomy between the research-oriented doctoral programs and the heavy
emphasis on meeting public school needs, which certainly reflected the leadership that had been here before.
But in industrial education, there had been a doctoral program started in 63, which is some six years before there was a college of education.
Who was instrumental in that, do you know?
Well, yes.
That really grew out of Chris Donovan's work and Eric Blaisman's work.
They were in the College of Engineering.
And the Department of Industrial Education started the industrial technology program, the industrial distribution program, and the engineering technology programs.
When the College of Education was formed, Dr. Boone moved to the college with Dr. Les Hawkins and Don Clark.
The other people stayed in engineering and built the technology program.
If you would identify a pivotal time in the life of this department, that was certainly it.
And opinions differ still about whether that was a wise move in that programs in industrial education rely so heavily on the technologies that you can't get in a college of education.
So if you look across the country, doctoral programs in our field that have a strong technological base
have a big advantage over those that are housed in colleges of education, where there's this tendency not to want to deal with the laboratories and not to want to deal with the technical instruction.
That is a tendency in the colleges of education?
Yes.
Not just here.
Interesting.
OK.
But all that happened long before I came.
OK.
So then what started happening when you came?
I came here because of the strength of the doctoral program in industrial ed.
I'd known it for a long time.
And we've ranked third for a number of years behind Ohio State and Maryland.
So, well, over the years, as fields have evolved, some things have been put positive and some negative.
You see a lot of growing strength in educational technology, for instance, which was started by this department, I understand, long before I came here.
The safety education program was developed quite a bit.
That was course started and the department is still there.
The copy center began in this department.
We're still dealing, I think, a lot with the role of the department and maybe the college in preparing for the school teachers.
And, of course, recent developments with homes and whatever have put that in even more jeopardy.
No one is quite sure what happens.
What the consequences are, the results or whatever, or how long it's going to take to see them.
Well, that's going to be a biggie.
Are there other things, were there some political or sociological or even psychological, I mean, philosophical changes?
influences that might have had an effect on some of the changes that came about in the department?
Do you have a department philosophy for starters?
Unfortunately, no.
The group has never really developed a coherent position.
They're really a group of specialists who each want autonomy in their own specialty.

Now I think in one sense the department has reflected in MicroCollege and the stresses that go between folks who are very interested in research and uninterested in teacher education to people who are very interested in teacher education and relatively less interested in research.
And in fact, I'm not sure the college has ever been deeply committed to research.
I'm sure that the department's ambiguities reflect that or maybe are maintained partially because of our lack of a coherent statement.
Whether we are really a research college of education or a service college of education.
What do you think they tend to lean more to?
The emphasis in the college has gone clearly toward undergraduate teacher education.
You mean right now, or it has been going?
Throughout our history.
OK. Do you foresee any changes in that?
Yes, I think that is changing, and it seems almost imperative that it changes.
If the college is to build its stature among other colleges of education,
If the college wants to serve the schools of Texas, it probably won't do it at the research base, much as we talk about this.
But researchers are hard-nosed people who don't worry so much about the outcomes.
And educators, teachers, and teacher educators tend to worry more about processes and the development of the individual rather than the search for.
Semi-pro.
Semi-pro.
Even a good generalization is hard to come by without being a hard-nosed researcher.
Well, that's one of the questions that I had about whether or not or to what extent the college was achieving its mission or maybe this Department of Teaching, Research, and Service.
And how did the department balance it
And how do you balance your own, according to your own philosophy?
Do you put equal emphasis on all, or are there some that are more important?
Well, the model of the teacher-researcher professional servant, I think, is a generally accepted one.
But you can't do all those things all the time equally well.
I just came back from chairing a conference
in Chicago, and I chair this thing every year and have now for eight years.
It's an enormous commitment to professional service to one organization.
I've been trying to just guess a month a year maybe that I spend on this one activity.
Our college, and certainly in the department, has made really major commitments to service to professional organizations.
I don't know that that's wrong,
But I don't think we've been willing to face its cost in terms of research productivity and in terms of teaching effectiveness.
Because you aren't teaching when you're away from campus.
And our college has a strong commitment to professional service.
What organization are you referring to in this case?
Well, this is the Mississippi Valley Industrial Teacher Education Conference that I was finished chairing.
You're saying that everybody tends to do a lot of this?
In our department, everybody has been very active in their professional organizations.
All of the senior faculty have been presidents of some organization, of some major organization.
And that's really more service than anything else?
Yes, I perceive that as a strong service.
It's service to the profession.
And some of the people who haven't yet been presidents are, for instance, on editorial boards where they read manuscripts.
It's one of those behind the scenes things that takes hours and hours and hours of faculty time and doesn't really generate anything but one line in a vitae, if they remember it.
a number of the people have been pretty committed to service to the public schools.
That has, it seems to me, vacillated over time, that is, if you look back over a long-term perspective.
Different groups have been effective in serving different clienteles over, during different periods.
Sometimes you meet the need, sometimes you move on to other things, but
They'll work with local service agencies, say that Dr. Parrish does with Vocational Special Needs and the agencies that serve those people.
It's in, by our definition, the service category.
We've not, I think, balanced teaching and research as well as we would lie.
And as I say, in my opinion, they are almost dichotomous interests
One requires a wait and see attitude.
The other is I can make it better.
And if you're committed to making it better, you'll never wait and see.
And I see relatively few in our college who've been really deeply committed to research.
In the whole college, not just in your department.
Yes, and it's certainly true in the department, and I see it true in the college.
I get the feeling from other interviews that the EDs
EPSI department feels very strongly that they're much more committed to research than anybody else.
They certainly feel that way.
They're all very vocal.
They certainly feel that way.
They certainly feel that way.
Okay.
Now, the growth since you arrived and since you've been here has been phenomenal.
And I'm assuming in the department, has the department grown much?
No.
The only growing program in the department left the department.
Which was?
Educational technology.
Where did it go?
To interdisciplinary education.
How does that come about?
Why did it leave and why does it fit in there better?
I'm not familiar at all with that process.
Well, I'm not certain that I want to comment about that on the record.
It was never discussed with me before it was done.
As far from my perspective, it was an arbitrary administrative action.
How long has that been?
Has that been?
A year ago last month, 15.
OK.
So then what is the size of the department right now, student-wise?
Do you have just more or less a?
I don't have the data.
Well, that's right.
You're not department head right now.
OK.
But our undergraduate enrollments have been declining for the past several years.
And we are fighting along with everybody else in our field to maintain graduate enrollments.

The peculiar thing that we cannot maintain graduate enrollments, we cannot, and this is true not just here, it's true at Ohio State, it's true at Maryland, it's true at Illinois, it's true at Minnesota.
And in our conference, we're very concerned about where our future generations of teacher educators come from.
Because graduate programs, advanced graduate programs, are not preparing a number of people that the demand surveys indicate are needed.
In just industrial and vocational?
Industrial and vocational technical education.
I'm not going to try to speak about the others, because this group that I just met with deals with industrial teacher education.
And that's the group that we had some papers on this this time.
Does the pendulum swing back and forth on that, or has it continued to decline steadily?
It's really hard to tell.
I tend right now toward a great deal of pessimism in that I cannot identify a dean of education who thinks that industrial education or technical education is important.
We're in the midst of a major back-to-basics move.
It's just not popular to say.
It may be right or it may be wrong.
The people may be right now.
But it is not popular to say we should strengthen industrial education.
Collaboration among the department that you have been

And again, I'm referring to this one because you were head of the department for the last 10 years, so that's the one that I'm focusing on because I don't know enough about that department to have a feel for it.
Was there a lot of collaboration among, well, within departments and then among this department with other departments in the college?
Well, my...
I think there's a disappointingly low level of collaboration with the department.
There has been some, in bits of referral, collaborative efforts.
Not only with other, actually, some better with people outside the college than with others within the college.
It's one of those things that I've puzzled over a great deal and not been able to diagnose.
My perception has been that our group has wanted to collaborate, but has not been successful as it would like to be in that process.
In the college?
Yes.
Does the specialization that you were talking about earlier have something to do with the fact that everybody is .
I think that people might have, I don't know whether people have a narrow image
of the professionals who work in the group or not.
That could be the case.
It's an interesting dynamic, which I don't have diagnosed.
But department heads do not collaborate in this college.
Department heads have never shared secrets, have always viewed them, in my experience, have always viewed themselves as competing.
No, there's never even an opportunity for department heads to meet without the dean staff being present.
Competing for resources, you think?
In my opinion, that has been a major inhibiting factor from the time I've been here.
The idea that the leadership comes from the dean's office instead of growing out of the group that can facilitate the interaction.
And it's been my impression that collaboration among department heads is viewed negatively from all levels above and below rather than being a way for things to occur.
All of the inquiry groups did not look at helping department heads
departments collaborate.
They look at giving faculty the kind of collaborative opportunities they were looking for.

But faculty have never seen... We're in a peculiar organizational dilemma in this college because we have a formal structure and it's as if that formal structure is set aside and used only to do some things.
What is the formal structure that you refer to?
Well, the departmental structure.
Oh, okay.
As compared to, say, a faculty structure that some universities have or
program structures that some universities have.
So the university expects department heads to perform in a peculiar way, but never to collaborate.
There is not anything that rewards collaboration.
Interesting.
You hit a sensitive point with that question.
Well, I haven't gotten as strong
a response from a lot of people.
Maybe a lot of people are not being candid enough with me, but I have not gotten that strong.
Everybody has said there's not enough, and we should do better, but nobody has said it.
I may not be right about this, but it's really important to know that after only a few months away from this role,
it's difficult to see the positive things that may have been going on.

For instance, I think we did a lot of collaborative things with educational technology, but then when educational technology chose to leave, there wasn't any discussion of what would be the best for all people concerned.
The decision was, I mean, the move was made by going around the group that it facilitated.
So I don't think that's collaboration by any definition.
And I've never chosen to seek out as if one might try to diagnose what's going on there.
But it certainly does diminish one's interest in doing more collaboration.
Good.
Perceptions.
And you've touched on a little bit about perceptions of outsiders and how this college is viewed.
a little bit about how certain departments in the college are viewed in reference to other similar colleges or similar education.
As you work with these organizations and travel a lot and go outside of here, what do you feel is the perception of others towards the college?
And is A&M still number three behind like it was when you came in this department?
You've got to look at it in different ways.
I was only talking about the doctoral program.
That's right, you were.
That program has, until this year, maintained its visibility and stature.
We draw people from all across the country, some international students, and we place people.
The VOED program has never made it to the top ranks.
It's much younger, and
has not had the faculty and students since the fellowship program was discontinued.
Oh, by much younger.
How young is it?
Do you know?
No.
OK. Was it before the College of Education came in to be?
I don't think so.
It was the EPDA fellowship program.
Oh, OK.
It was all to identify that starting date.
OK.
It seems like it would have been in the late 60s, but I don't think the program had started before the college was formed.
I wasn't here.
Okay.
Did you work under both Beans?
Yes.
Okay.
And Lindbacher in between.
And Lindbacher.
Okay.
Tell me a little bit about the differences, and I've gotten a lot on the leadership styles, and it's obvious, it's a tremendous change, but
From your department, what were some of the changes or some of the differences in just the everyday running of the department under the two administrations?
And even Limbocker's.
I haven't really focused on that interim year.
That interim year was a devastating year for this department.
How so?
The laboratory building next door was being renovated that year.
There were no laboratories at all.
We had equipment in the basement of this building and were teaching our undergraduate classes in the basement of this building in the hallway.
And I could get no support from the dean to seek other space on a temporary basis or do anything.
And we, in essence, undid our undergraduate program during that time.
We had, until then, we had absolutely a top-flight group of undergraduate students.
And because the dean's office was totally disinterested in what we needed with this situation.
So that was a disaster year for us.
And it had nothing to do with personalities, because I got along fine with all three people.
But because of our lack of leadership, lack of commitment, we really suffered.
Now, what is the deal across the street that you refer to?
What laboratory or what goes on over there?
Our undergraduates have to be prepared to teach their technical subjects somewhere.
And during that era, we could not get any of them into any of the engineering technology courses.
We were having the same problem that every freshman counselor has been having this year.
All the engineering technology courses were full if one of our students got in.
And we were requiring them.
So we had to develop our own courses.
which means we had to have our own laboratories or someplace to teach them.
And we had a woodworking, metalworking, power, construction, manufacturing, and plastics courses, which we got squenched down into one room for all those.
Well, there is more, because the original dean that is original to me, well, the original dean fostered the crafts program, which had a lab here and a lab in the other building.
And that program moved to environmental design somewhat more amicably than the educational technology movement.
What was the dean's?
attitude or what was their comparison or contrast between the attitude towards the department from the two administrations?
I don't know.
It seemed to me that both have at times indicated strong support.
Probably neither has been able to demonstrate the level of commitment that one would like to see.
I don't think anyone in the department has ever felt full-fledged support on a continuing basis, which is a major concern, I think.
So that's asking the impossible of an administration, but that's what people would like to have.
Continuous commitment.
Yeah, continuous commitment.
And we have not been newsmakers.
Teaching people how to earn a living or teaching people how to teach people how to earn a living is not very glamorous.
It doesn't match up with math and science.
But a whole lot more people have to learn to do it.
And in terms of the social value of our field, I think we've been basically unrecognized at the college.
Now that you're out of the department, I don't know if you have
any kind of a vision, or if you did beforehand, about where it's going.
And I know there's new laws and all these are going to affect that department as well as all of the others.
Do you have a little crystal ball, or did you, about where you think these things are going?
Well, I did have, and it's been surprised quite a bit lately.
It has been what?
My crystal ball has been surprised lately.
I really feel that
The department right now is in a very ambiguous situation.
And it's difficult for me to be really objective since I'm only a few months away from it, and since I still have an appointment in it, but since I don't have any real influence in it.
And I refuse to try to influence in the filibustering sense or in the political way.
But it's a very uncomfortable time.
for the faculty, and the group really needs to be able to work its value with a better sense of purpose than it has.
It's being asked again to clarify its mission, and...
But again, what do you mean?
Has it been asked to do this?
Well, we spent a good share of last year in a self-study,
Which, well, I'm being very frank with you there.
I really hope you'll be.
True.
Okay.
And people are so concerned.
What is, what are you?
Center for Career Development, is the way that's called.
But yours is, oh, I see.
Why, why did they name that?

Well, it was named that during the era when career education was a big thing, and Chris Warman was doing a bunch of career everything, and, and Hubert put together the name and named it, and it didn't, the name didn't go away, but we've not been able to find anyone who wants to fund anything
I think we would have been better off to have said, you know, cancel that name because the name is such a handicap.
But you're catching me on an actual rock and a block.
That's okay.
I need that.
I should get into town before 2.30 then.
That's right.
Before you're going to do an interview.
Okay.
You said the last thing you said was that you had spent a great deal of last year in a self-study.
Yes.
Okay.
And
What were you pleased with the results, or did the results indicate?
This is a really awkward thing.
Because our faculty really felt, I'm interpreting faculty, but the dean just insisted that we bring in some outside consultants and do a self study.
Then he intervened a couple of times, and that generated some resistance.
And at about the time the faculty senate asked their recommendation that department head tenure should be limited to 10 years, some faculty members stopped participating in the search for consensus.
Now it appears that we're being asked again what to do.
what to recommend to the dean with regard to programs, departmental emphasis.
And as I said before, we don't have a cohesive group.
We've got a group of individual specialists, each in their own area.
It's as if you had one reading person, one science person, one social studies person.
And you say, now what are we all ought to be doing?
And one says we ought to be doing reading, and another says we ought to be doing math, and another says we ought to be doing science, and another says we ought to be doing social studies.
Now, this faculty senate thing, is that something new about a 10-year department head limit?
Yes.
I hadn't heard that one.
That came into effect last year, as I was in my 10th year, more than halfway through it.
OK.
I hadn't heard about that one.
I don't think that's necessarily a bad thing.
I was at a very awkward spot in my own career.
And it absolutely destroyed my ability to lead the group, if the group was leadable.
But things have really, departmental consensus has really degenerated since that time, as I perceive it.
I think that the department has got to feel some security and support, and it doesn't appear to me likely that that will occur under an interim head.
There's no search for a clear statement that there will be one.
So it's a real uncomfortable time right now for people.
